Parses `ctx-cage`'s argv into a `Mode` the lifecycle executes, and gates billed modes behind `--allow-spend`. This is the CLI-only half of mode resolution — the lifecycle layer does no argv parsing of its own and trusts `Mode` as already-validated input.

Mode selection rule, in order: `--self-test <kind>` wins if present; else `--task`/`--task-file` ⇒ `Mode::Task`; else `Mode::Interactive`. These are mutually exclusive — `check_flag_conflicts` rejects combining `--self-test` with any task flag, `--task` with `--task-file`, or either with `--interactive`, all before `compute_mode` runs. Billed modes (`Task`, `Interactive`) require `allow_spend: bool` passed into `resolve_mode`; that bool itself comes from `--allow-spend` OR `CTX_CAGE_ALLOW_SPEND=1`, resolved by the caller — this file only checks the already-combined flag, it doesn't read the env var itself. Only `SelfTestStub` is unbilled.

`CONTRACT: &str` is the canonical agent-facing description of the binary; a "contracts" battery check fails if this string drifts from the corresponding block in `CLAUDE.md`/`README.md` — those docs must be kept in sync with any edit here.

Key entry point: `resolve_mode(cli: &Cli, allow_spend: bool) -> Result<Mode, ResolveError>`. `TaskFlags` and `SpendFlags` are `#[command(flatten)]`-ed sub-structs, deliberately split to stay under clippy's `struct_excessive_bools` threshold without an `#[allow]` (banned by workspace policy). `ResolveError` has three variants: `Conflict`, `NotAllowed`, `Io` (auto-`From<std::io::Error>` via `#[from]`, triggered only by `--task-file` reads). `--allow-dirty` is parsed here (in `SpendFlags`) but not used in this file — consumed by lifecycle/host code to permit billed runs on a dirty git tree; default is refusal.